		{"id":"d61","type":"file","file":"02 - Incidents/Incident - 2020-08 Persian Gulf D61 SKELETON.md","x":800,"y":50,"width":400,"height":240,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"analysis","type":"text","text":"## Cross-cutting observations\n\n==Most multi-object events== in the modern collection are 2 or 3 objects, geographically clustered (CENTCOM), and showing either parallel motion or loose grouping.\n\n==D58 stands out==: only case in the collection where one object was explicitly circling the other, with noise jamming, and instantaneous disappearance. This is the strongest 'pair' anomaly.\n\n==D3 stands out== as a true 4-object event with three separate sub-times (1, 2, 1) within a 27-second window, suggesting a small loose formation passing through the FOV.\n\n==D65 has 3 separate UAPs== across a single 21-hour mission, suggesting persistent local presence rather than a single formation.","x":1300,"y":50,"width":520,"height":660,"color":"6"}
	],
